com.apple.audio.toolbox
Class MusicEventIterator

java.lang.Object
  com.apple.audio.CAObject
      com.apple.audio.toolbox.MusicEventIterator
public final class MusicEventIterator
extends CAObject

Some Notes on using the iterator to move through events in the track. 

To use the iterator going forward when looping...
        New Iterator (points at first event)
        while (iter.hasCurrentEvent()) {
                do work with the current event

                iter.nextEvent ()
        }

Or to go back...
        iter.seek (kMusicTimeStamp_EndOfTrack) -> will point it past the last event
        while (iter.hasPreviousEvent()) {
                iter.previousEvent();
                do work with the current event
        }
You can "rock" the Iterator back and forwards as well of course

Method Detail

seek

public void seek(double inTimeStamp)
          throws CAException
Moves the iterator to the specified time position. Passing in -1 for inTimeStamp will position the iterator to the end of track - (which is pointing to the space just AFTER the last event - use MusicEventIteratorPreviousEvent() to backup one, if you want the last event)

nextEvent

public void nextEvent()
               throws CAException
Moves the iterator to the next event from its current position. If the iterator is at the last event, then it moves past the last event and no longer points to an event. So always check to see if there is an event at the iterator

CoreAudio::MusicEventIteratorNextEvent

Throws:

previousEvent

public void previousEvent()
                   throws CAException
Moves the iterator to the previous event from its current position. If the iterator is already at the first event, then it remains unchanged and an error is returned.
